# Password Policy

Policy Title: Password Policy
Policy Number: PWD-001
Effective Date: {{ effective_date }}
Version: 1.0
Classification: Internal
Approved By: {{ company_name }} Security Officer

## Purpose

This policy defines the requirements for creating, managing, and protecting authentication credentials used to access {{ company_name }}'s information systems and applications. It incorporates current best practices from NIST SP 800-63B and prioritizes usability alongside security to promote sustainable password hygiene across the organization.

## Scope

This policy applies to all Personnel - employees, contractors, temporary workers, and any other individuals who hold accounts on any system that resides within {{ company_name }}'s facilities or has access to the organizational network. It covers all authentication credentials, including passwords, passphrases, PINs, and multi-factor authentication tokens.

## Policy

### Password Construction Requirements

| Requirement | Specification |
|-------------|---------------|
| Minimum length | **12 characters** (NIST SP 800-63B recommends minimum 8 for user-chosen, 12 for stronger assurance) |
| Maximum length | At least 64 characters; systems must not truncate passwords |
| Character composition | No mandatory complexity rules (no required uppercase, lowercase, digits, or special characters) |
| Passphrases | Encouraged; multiple words with spaces are stronger and more memorable than short complex passwords |
| Password generation | All passwords should be generated by the organization-approved password manager using maximum available length and character sets |
| Banned passwords | Passwords appearing in known breach corpora, dictionary words, keyboard patterns, and context-specific words are prohibited |
| Password history | Do not reuse the last {{ password_history_count }} passwords |
| Cross-system reuse | Each system and service must use a unique password. Password reuse across distinct systems is prohibited |

### Password Manager Requirement

All Personnel must use the organization-approved password manager ({{ password_manager_name }}) for generating and storing all work-related credentials. The password manager provides:

- Automatic generation of strong, unique passwords for every service
- Encrypted storage synchronized across authorized devices
- Secure sharing of credentials when necessary (without revealing the password text)
- Breach monitoring to alert users when a stored password appears in known data breaches

The master password for the password manager is the **single password that Personnel must memorize**. This master password must:
- Be at least {{ master_password_min_length }} characters
- Be a memorable passphrase, not a complex string
- Never be written down or stored electronically outside the password manager
- Be changed immediately if suspected of compromise

### Single Sign-On (SSO)

Where technically feasible, systems and applications must be integrated with the organization's Single Sign-On (SSO) provider. SSO reduces the number of credentials Personnel must manage, centralizes access control, and enables consistent enforcement of authentication policies including MFA. New systems acquired or developed must support SAML 2.0, OIDC, or equivalent federation protocols.

